e for C: \"creates a positive atmosphere with his crew\" which is a teamwork/crew cooperation strength. Also for others: any? Candidate A: \"very good leadership qualities\" could be considered teamwork, but not explicitly stated as teamwork. The rule: must use explicit statements. Leadership is not necessarily teamwork, but could be considered a strength in crew cooperation? But it's not explicitly \"teamwork\" or \"communication\". So we should not count it unless the question is about strengths in teamwork or communication. The only explicit statement about teamwork is \"creates a positive atmosphere with his crew\" for C. Also maybe \"very good leadership qualities\" could be considered teamwork, but it's ambiguous. Safer to only mention the explicit positive crew atmosphere.\n\nNow reliability for Candidate A: no explicit reliability statement. Responsibility? No explicit. So answer: No info on A reliability/responsibility. For C: known to be 100% reliable (reliability) and takes responsibility? Not explicit. No explicit responsibility statement. So we can say reliability known, but no explicit responsibility.\n\nNow any documented strengths in teamwork or communication: C creates positive atmosphere with crew (teamwork). Also maybe none for others. Also note that no explicit communication strengths for any candidate; only weaknesses.\n\nThus answer accordingly, mention uncertainty where appropriate."}
